<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-08-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-08-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="108" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d108">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Adams</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1077.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-08-26"><hi rend="italic">August</hi> 26, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> In a letter to this department of the 12th
                            instant Mr. Wilson, the secretary of legation at London, gives an
                            account of certain proceedings with reference to the late insurgent
                            steamer Georgia, and particularly of an intimation given to the
                            Portuguese minister, at London, to the effect that the Georgia, having
                            been sold in a neutral port, would be a lawful prize to a United States
                            cruiser. The proceedings referred to are approved by the department.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>